elf-consistency. Concrete: how much does pass@k improve over pass@1 for code when you can verify? Numbers showing a small model with many samples + a verifier approaching or matching a bigger model's pass@1.\n- The generator-verifier gap: verification is easier than generation; strong verifier amplifies weak generator. Any papers quantifying this.\n- Evolutionary / population search over candidate code edits gated by tests: AlphaEvolve (DeepMind 2025), FunSearch, evolutionary code search. How tests-as-fitness lifts results.\n- Test-time compute scaling laws (e.g. OpenAI o1, DeepMind \"scaling test-time compute optimally\" Snell et al.) — when does spending more inference beat a bigger model.\n- Limits: when does best-of-N stop helping (verifier false positives, reward hacking, coverage ceiling, weak model never samples a correct solution at all).\n\nRun at least 4-5 searches. Fetch authoritative sources (arXiv, DeepMind blog for AlphaEvolve/FunSearch, the Large Language Monkeys paper). Cross-check numbers.\n\nReturn a list of FALSIFIABLE CLAIMS each with: claim, number/detail, source URL. Flag conflicts. Do NOT write files. Return findings only as your final message.","outputFile":"/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/8c297f37-26ee-4ab6-9c6c-7ec95dbfe2e1/tasks/a72217cc746f6deac.output","canReadOutputFile":true},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"c976fca9-53f6-489c-a8e6-5d6eea973c21","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"da7bcc30-7a43-473c-b672-a245db1427b1","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01WL7qTcr2xSPA9pvHKa5Cii","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01FVuycsBD8mn6J8cbc1ttJm","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Small model trend and outlook","prompt":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch (load them via ToolSearch query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\" first if not available). The current date is June 2026.\n\nRESEARCH ANGLE: Realistic outlook/timeline for small local models becoming \"good enough to self-improve their own codebase,\" and the trend of small-model coding capability over time.\n\nResearch concretely:\n- The rate of improvement of small (7-8B) open models at coding over 2023->2026 (Qwen2.5-Coder vs Qwen3 vs Qwen3-Coder; how fast SWE-bench/LiveCodeBench scores for small models are rising). Is the gap to frontier closing or widening?\n- METR's \"task length doubling\" / time-horizon trend (length of tasks AI can do autonomously doubling ~every 7 months) — implications for autonomous multi-step coding.\n- Predictions/timelines for autonomous AI software engineering, recursive self-improvement timelines (AI 2027, lab statements, expert forecasts).\n- Local/on-device AI coding trends: are small models trending toward usable autonomous agents locally, and what techniques (distillation, RL, agentic scaffolding, longer context) drive it.\n- Realistic skeptic takes: why small local models still fail at autonomous self-coding (context limits, long-horizon reliability, error compounding).\n\nRun at least 4-5 searches. Fetch authoritative sources (METR blog metr.org, arXiv, lab blogs, Qwen release posts, Epoch AI). Cross-check.\n\nReturn a list of FALSIFIABLE CLAIMS each with: claim, number/detail, source URL. Flag conflicts. Do NOT write files. Return findings only as your final message.","subagent_type":"general-purpose","run_in_background":