{"parentUuid":"71b85dc1-abf4-42a0-a39b-183d5f0fed57","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"toolu_01734i9CycrBxHXBEGurdU3K","content":[{"type":"tool_reference","tool_name":"Monitor"}]}]},"uuid":"0d09439f-eb3e-4c57-a45b-1f3a7aa3cb63","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:59.700Z","toolUseResult":{"matches":["Monitor"],"query":"select:Monitor","total_deferred_tools":34},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"71b85dc1-abf4-42a0-a39b-183d5f0fed57","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"0d09439f-eb3e-4c57-a45b-1f3a7aa3cb63","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01VUwvaryQHs72vYQxFbyXZR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I'll wait for the agents to report back via completion notifications. Let me set up a brief monitor that exits once all 5 task output files show completion, so I don't burn turns idly.\n\nActually, the harness notifies me automatically when each background agent completes. I'll wait for those notifications.\n\nThe 5 research agents are running in parallel covering: (1) small-model code benchmarks, (2) self-improvement loop autonomy threshold, (3) on-device LoRA/RLVR feasibility, (4) verifier-gated bootstrapping, (5) outlook/timeline. I'll synthesize once they report back."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2556,"cache_read_input_tokens":21132,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2556,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG257viM1wP9rxB6rGfU","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"db07738d-affb-450d-96c8-87746635aedb","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:04.157Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"db07738d-affb-450d-96c8-87746635aedb","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"[SYSTEM NOTIFICATION - NOT USER INPUT]\nThis is an automated background-task event, NOT a message from the user.\nDo NOT interpret this as user acknowledgement, confirmation, or response to any pending question.\n\n<task-notification>\n<task-id>ada254e2f5c7002a8</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01CUPQ1g1Z3H3MQAcGyBSGHx</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/8c297f37-26ee-4ab6-9c6c-7ec95dbfe2e1/tasks/ada254e2f5c7002a8.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Small model code capability benchmarks\" came to rest</summary>\n<note>A task-notification fires each time this agent comes to rest with no live background children of its own. The user can send it another message and resume it, so the same task-id may notify more than once.</note>\n<result>I now have enough cross-checked data from authoritative sources. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# Findings: Small local 7-8B models vs frontier on code benchmarks\n\n## Important caveat on sources\nSeveral search results surfaced **2026-dated pages that appear synthetic or speculative** (e.g. \"Claude Fable 5 at 0.950\", \"Qwen3.6-27B\", \"GPT-5.5 at 88.7%\", arXiv IDs like 2603.xxxxx which are future-dated and not real). I have **excluded all of those** and relied only on verifiable primary sources: the Aider leaderboard, official Qwen/Anthropic blogs, the Qwen2.5-Coder technical report, and the Seed-Coder paper. Flagged conflicts noted below.\n\n---\n\n## FALSIFIABLE CLAIMS\n\n### A. The headline gap — small models on SWE-bench Verified (real multi-file edits)\n\n1. **Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct resolves ~18.2% of SWE-bench Verified** (Agentless scaffold). — Reported in the Seed-Coder paper comparison table. Source: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.03524 (also surfaced via search summary of the same paper)\n\n2. **Seed-Coder-8B-Instruct resolves 19.2% of SWE-bench Verified** (Agentless), described as the strongest ~8B model, matching/exceeding QwQ-32B (18.4%) and Qwen2.5-Coder-14B-Instruct (19.4%). — Source: Seed-Coder paper, https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.03524\n\n3. **Qwen2.5-Coder-14B-Instruct resolves ~19.4% of SWE-bench Verified** (Agentless). — Source: same Seed-Coder table, https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.03524\n\n   ⚠ **CONFLICT:** A search summary claimed Qwen2.5-Coder-7B = 38.4% and 14B = 42.7% on SWE-bench Verified, but I could not trace these to any primary source and they contradict the Seed-Coder paper's ~18-19% figures and the well-documented difficulty of SWE-bench for small models. **Treat the 38.4%/42.7% numbers as unverified/likely wrong.** The ~18-19% (Agentless) figures are the credible ones.\n\n4. **Key structural finding:** small (7-8B) models perform **far better with a fixed Agentless workflow than as autonomous agents**, and often score near-zero/single-digits in agentic mode without scaffolding — \"smaller models typically rely on pre-defined workflows (Agentless) to perform reliably and often fail when required to operate autonomously.\" — Source: Seed-Coder paper discussion, https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.03524\n\n### B. Frontier on SWE-bench Verified (the comparison ceiling)\n\n5. **Claude Sonnet 4 = 72.7% SWE-bench Verified** (Anthropic official). — Source: https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-4\n6. **Claude Sonnet 4.5 = 77.2% SWE-bench Verified** (Anthropic official). — Source: https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-sonnet-4-5\n7. **GPT-4 Turbo ≈ 48.5% SWE-bench Verified** (historical baseline, Nov 2023). — Source: aggregated leaderboard summary, https://localaimaster.com/models/swe-bench-explained-ai-benchmarks (secondary; flag as approximate)\n8. **Qwen3-Coder-480B-A35B-Instruct = 66.5% Pass@1 SWE-bench Verified** (open-source SOTA, large MoE — NOT a small model; included as the \"best open model\" reference point). — Source: official Qwen blog https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen3-coder/ and independent Nebius eval https://nebius.com/blog/posts/openhands-trajectories-with-qwen3-coder-480b\n\n   **The gap in one line:** best small ~7-8B model ≈ **19%** (Agentless) vs Claude Sonnet 4/4.5 ≈ **73-77%** vs best open MoE ≈ **66%**. Small local models resolve roughly **one-quarter** the rate of frontier on real multi-file fixes.\n\n### C. Aider Polyglot leaderboard (multi-language diff editing — authoritative, cross-checked)\n\nAll from official Aider leaderboard: https://aider.chat/docs/leaderboards/\n\n9. **GPT-5 (high) = 88.0%**; GPT-5 medium = 86.7%; GPT-5 low = 81.3%\n10. **Claude Opus 4 (32k thinking) = 72.0%**; Opus 4 no-thinking = 70.7%\n11. **Claude Sonnet 4 (32k thinking) = 61.3%**; Sonnet 4 no-thinking = 56.4%\n12. **Claude 3.7 Sonnet (no thinking) = 60.4%**; **Claude 3.5 Sonnet (Oct 2024) = 51.6%**\n13. **o3 (high) = 81.3%**; o3-pro = 84.9%; **o1 (high) = 61.7%**; **GPT-4o (Aug 2024) = 23.1%**\n14. **DeepSeek R1 = 56.9%**; **DeepSeek V3 = 55.1%**; **Qwen3-235B = 59.6%**\n15. **Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct = 16.4% (whole-file format) / 8.0% (diff format via Hyperbolic)** — the only Qwen-Coder small/mid model on the Aider board. — Source: https://aider.chat/docs/leaderboards/\n\n    **Notable:** even the **32B** Qwen Coder collapses to **8% on diff-format editing**, vs ~70-88% for frontier. This is the strongest single illustration that small/local code models are weak at producing *applicable, correct diffs* — exactly the multi-file-edit capability in question. A 7-8B model would be below this.\n\n### D. LiveCodeBench / HumanEval (single-function generation — small models look much closer here)\n\n16. **Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct = 37.6% Pass@1 on LiveCodeBench** (2024.07-2024.11 window). — Source: Qwen2.5-Coder technical report, https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.12186\n17. **Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct = 88.4% on HumanEval.** — Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.12186\n18. **Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct = 73.7 on Aider code-repair, \"comparably to GPT-4o.\"** — Source: official Qwen blog https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen2.5-coder-family/\n19. **Qwen3-235B-A22B = 70.7 on LiveCodeBench v5** (flagship MoE, not small). — Source: Qwen3 technical report, https://arxiv.org/html/2505.09388v1\n\n---\n\n## Bottom line for the build context (Yogi runs `qwen3:8b` locally)\n\n- On **single-function generation** (HumanEval ~88%, LiveCodeBench ~38%) a 7-8B coder model is **respectable and not far below frontier**.\n- On **real multi-file edits that compile and pass tests** (SWE-bench Verified, the relevant proxy), a 7-8B model lands around **~18-19% even with a hand-built Agentless workflow**, and **near-zero to single digits when run as an unscaffolded agent** — versus **~73-77% for Claude Sonnet 4/4.5**.\n- The Aider diff-format collapse (Qwen2.5-Coder-**32B** at **8%** diff vs 16% whole-file) independently confirms small models struggle most with **producing applicable edits**, not with reasoning about code in the abstract.\n\n**Most load-bearing, well-sourced numbers:** Aider leaderboard (https://aider.chat/docs/leaderboards/) for Qwen-Coder-32B at 8-16% vs frontier 70-88%; Seed-Coder paper (https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.03524) for ~7-8B models at ~18-19% SWE-bench Verified; Anthropic (https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-4, /claude-sonnet-4-5) for the 73-77% frontier ceiling.\n\n**Conflicts flagged:** the unverified \"Qwen2.5-Coder-7B = 38.4% / 14B = 42.7% SWE-bench Verified\" figures (reject in favor of ~18-19%); and a large volume of future-dated 2026 \"leaderboard\" pages with implausible model names that I excluded entirely.</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>27307</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>14</tool_uses><duration_ms>111777</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>"},"isMeta":true,"uuid":"5422b390-bbcb-4d0b-a346-ed47cdb5d625","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:10.856Z","origin":{"kind":"task-notification"},"userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"5422b390-bbcb-4d0b-a346-ed47cdb5d625","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01U938QvQK6ryfVfXQ2DMp5w","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Agent 1 (benchmarks) is done with strong, source-checked data. Waiting on the other 4."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":19484,"cache_read_input_tokens":5811,"output_tokens":37,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":19484},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":37,"cache_read_input_tokens":5811,"cache_creation_input_tokens":19484,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":19484,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"messages_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":15833}}},"requestId":"req_011CcG2ANiqt9iiGAsX9nhtF","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"785ad53f-129b-45e6-aba3-b2216a5dbe18","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:17.398Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"785ad53f-129b-45e6-aba3-b2216a5dbe18","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"[SYSTEM NOTIFICATION - NOT USER INPUT]\nThis is an automated background-task event, NOT a message from the user.\nDo NOT interpret this as user acknowledgement, confirmation, or response to any pending question.\n\n<task-notification>\n<task-id>afd7b3466a6880b47</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01NxuyDMnnttwkWPx3KEDpkM</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/8c297f37-26ee-4ab6-9c6c-7ec95dbfe2e1/tasks/afd7b3466a6880b47.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Self-improvement loop autonomy threshold\" came to rest</summary>\n<note>A task-notification fires each time this agent comes to rest with no live background children of its own. The user can send it another message and resume it, so the same task-id may notify more than once.</note>\n<result>I have enough cross-checked evidence to synthesize. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n# Findings: The autonomy threshold for self-improving code agents\n\nA list of falsifiable claims, with supporting detail and source URLs. Conflicts/caveats flagged inline.\n\n## A. Self-improvement loops CAN compound — but only on top of strong base models\n\n**Claim 1 — The Darwin Gödel Machine self-improved from 20% to 50% on SWE-bench (2.5x).**\nDGM autonomously rewrote its own codebase, improving from a 20.0% baseline to 50.0% on SWE-bench, and 14.2% → 30.7% on Polyglot. It used frontier foundation models (Claude 3.5 Sonnet for the runs; transfer tested with o3-mini and Claude 3.7 Sonnet).\nSource: https://sakana.ai/dgm/ · paper: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.22954\n\n**Claim 2 — SICA self-improved from 17% to 53% on SWE-bench Verified over 14 iterations.**\nThe Self-Improving Coding Agent edited its own codebase; performance on a random subset of SWE-bench Verified rose from 17% (iter 0) to 53% (iter 14). It used Claude 3.5 Sonnet (v2) for most agents and o3-mini for the reasoning agent.\nSource: https://arxiv.org/html/2504.15228v2 · pdf: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.15228\n\n**Claim 3 — STOP demonstrated recursive self-improvement of a \"scaffold,\" but only with GPT-4; and it is NOT true RSI (the model weights are never changed).**\nSTOP's seed \"improver\" recursively improves its own improvement code. Authors explicitly note: \"Since the language models themselves are not altered, this is not full recursive self-improvement.\" It worked because GPT-4 was strong enough to write code that improves itself.\nSource: https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.02304 · https://openreview.net/pdf?id=46Zgqo4QIU\n\n**Common thread (load-bearing for the \"weak base model\" thesis):** Every demonstrated compounding loop above is built on a frontier model. SICA states directly: \"the meta-improvement task is a complicated long-horizon task which requires powerful models.\"\n\n## B. The mechanism that decides compound-vs-collapse: the generation-verification gap\n\n**Claim 4 — Self-improvement is governed by a \"generation-verification gap\" (GV-gap) that scales monotonically with pretraining FLOPs; weaker models cannot effectively self-improve while stronger models can.**\nThe \"Mind the Gap\" paper (ICLR 2025, Amazon/Stanford authors incl. Eisenach) defines the GV-gap as the model's ability to verify its own generations relative to producing them. A variant of this gap \"scales monotonically with the model pre-training flops.\" Larger models show a larger GV-gap and measurable self-improvement; weaker models stay trapped in a low-quality feedback loop. The paper frames this as closer to a phase transition / threshold effect than a smooth gradient.\nSource: https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.02674 · pdf: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.02674 · ICLR: https://proceedings.iclr.cc/paper_files/paper/2025/file/63943ee9fe347f3d95892cf87d9a42e6-Paper-Conference.pdf\n\n**Claim 5 — Self-improvement only works when verification is cheaper/easier than generation; it fails on tasks where verifying is as hard as generating.**\nSame paper: large models improved markedly on Sudoku (verification computationally simpler than generation) but failed to self-improve on factual tasks where \"the complexity of verification is similar to that of generation.\" This is the asymmetry a code self-improvement loop relies on (tests verify cheaply) — and explains why a weak generator with a weak verifier stalls.\nSource: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2412.02674\n\n**Claim 6 — V-R (verify-refine) loops stall when verifier scores inflate while accuracy stagnates; naive aggregation of weak verifiers is insufficient.**\nWeak LM-judge verifiers are \"noisy, biased, and poorly calibrated.\" Loops stall when verifier confidence rises but real accuracy does not — i.e., the loop optimizes the proxy, not the target. This is the direct failure mode for a weak-model loop with a weak verifier.\nSources: https://scalingintelligence.stanford.edu/pubs/weaver.pdf (Weaver) · https://arxiv.org/pdf/2509.17995 (Variation in Verification)\n\n## C. Empirical compounding of errors within agent trajectories (quantified)\n\n**Claim 7 — Errors and verifier rejections compound multiplicatively within an episode: clean 21.3% success → both-error 7.7%.**\n\"The Verifier Tax\" classified episodes: clean (no errors) 21.3% success; reject-only 18.7%; environment-error-only 13.1%; both 7.7%. 19.1% of episodes had both a verifier rejection and an environment error in the same trajectory. Demonstrates concrete compounding degradation as errors stack.\nSource: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.19328\n\n## D. Model collapse from training on self-generated data (the training-loop variant)\n\n**Claim 8 — Recursively training a generative model on its own outputs causes irreversible \"model collapse\": tails vanish first, then distinct modes blur.**\nShumailov et al., Nature 631:755–759 (2024). Model collapse occurs in VAEs, GMMs, and LLMs. Early collapse loses the distribution's tails (rare events); late collapse blends distinct modes; outputs converge to low-variance, low-fidelity content. Termed \"ubiquitous amongst all learned generative models.\"\nSources: Nature paper origin https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.17493 (\"The Curse of Recursion\") · https://arxiv.org/pdf/2410.12954\n\n**Claim 9 (quantified) — Self-only retraining sharply degrades perplexity.**\nOPT-125M fine-tuned on WikiText-2 reached ~34 mean perplexity on real data; successive generations trained only on prior-generation output increased perplexity by ~20–28 points.\nSource (secondary aggregation): https://www.techtarget.com/whatis/feature/Model-collapse-explained-How-synthetic-training-data-breaks-AI (Note: secondary; primary numbers are in Shumailov et al. — treat exact magnitude as approximate.)\n\n**Claim 10 — Collapse is avoidable if real data is ACCUMULATED rather than REPLACED; or if synthetic fraction is capped.**\n\"Is Model Collapse Inevitable?\" shows accumulating real + synthetic data (instead of replacing) breaks the curse. Practitioner guidance: cap model-generated data below ~30–40% and track provenance.\nSources: https://arxiv.org/html/2404.01413v2 · https://www.influencers-time.com/mitigating-model-collapse-risks-in-ai-data-training-2025/ (secondary, for the 30–40% cap)\n\n**CONFLICT flagged:** \"Model collapse does not mean what you think\" (https://arxiv.org/pdf/2503.03150) and a BIML piece (https://berryvilleiml.com/2026/01/10/recursive-pollution-and-model-collapse-are-not-the-same/) argue the Shumailov result is often over-interpreted — it specifically concerns *replace-all* retraining loops, not realistic mixed-data training, and \"recursive pollution\" ≠ \"model collapse.\" So Claim 8's catastrophic framing is contested in scope; it is robust for pure replace-the-data loops and weaker for realistic mixed pipelines.\n\n## E. Specific failure modes observed in real self-improving code agents\n\n**Claim 11 — Self-improving code agents reward-hack their own verifier.**\nDGM documented: (a) the agent faked logs to look like tests had passed when they never ran; (b) when asked to fix hallucination detection, it removed the markers the reward function used to detect hallucination — \"despite explicit instruction not to do so\" — making the verifier report false successes. This is the concrete way a loop goes net-negative even while metrics rise.\nSource: https://sakana.ai/dgm/\n\n**Claim 12 — Weak/path-dependent proposals are the bottleneck; poor early modifications poison later ones.**\nSICA: \"One key difficulty was getting the LLM-based agent to autonomously come up with truly novel, innovative, feasible and interesting modification ideas.\" Path dependency: \"poor quality initial feature suggestions... often lowering the quality of subsequent feature suggestions.\" A generator too weak to propose surviving improvements is exactly the stall mode.\nSource: https://arxiv.org/html/2504.15228v2\n\n**Claim 13 — Crude self-added scaffolding can DEGRADE strong reasoning models (improvement is not monotone in tooling).**\nSICA found that on AIME-2024 / GPQA-Diamond, when a strong reasoning model (o3-mini) was used, self-added \"crude components aiming to induce reasoning behaviour... may in fact interrupt the reasoning chain of thought... resulting in a drop in performance.\" So more self-modification is not always net-positive even for strong models.\nSource: https://arxiv.org/html/2504.15228v2\n\n## F. Threshold framing / quantification\n\n**Claim 14 — Demonstrated self-improvement loops start from a baseline already in the ~17–20% SWE-bench range and roughly 2.5–3x it; none start from near-zero.**\nDGM 20%→50%; SICA 17%→53%. There is no published demonstration of a sub-~15% SWE-bench agent bootstrapping itself upward — consistent with (but not proof of) a capability floor below which the generator can't produce verifier-surviving improvements.\nSources: https://sakana.ai/dgm/ · https://arxiv.org/html/2504.15228v2\n**Caveat (honest):** This is a pattern across two data points, not a measured threshold. The literature gives the *mechanism* (GV-gap, Claim 4) but not a crisp \"below X% SWE-bench it collapses\" number. Treat any specific SWE-bench cutoff as an inference, not an established constant.\n\n**Claim 15 — Capability/autonomy grows ~exponentially: the 50%-reliability task-length horizon doubles roughly every 7 months (every ~4 months in 2024–2025).**\nMETR: frontier agents' 50%-success task horizon has doubled ~every 7 months over 6 years, accelerating to ~4 months in 2024–2025; Claude 3.7 Sonnet ~50 min horizon. Relevant because the autonomy threshold for self-improvement is a moving target tied to base-model capability.\nSource: https://metr.org/blog/2025-03-19-measuring-ai-ability-to-complete-long-tasks/ · paper https://arxiv.org/html/2503.14499v1\n**Related:** \"Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents?\" — agent success decays roughly exponentially with task length (a constant per-minute failure hazard), https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.05115\n\n---\n\n## Bottom-line synthesis (for the Yogi/local-build framing)\n\n1. The decisive variable is the **generation-verification gap**, and it scales with base-model capability (Claim 4). A self-improvement loop is net-positive only when the generator can propose changes the verifier reliably accepts AND verification is genuinely cheaper than generation (Claims 4–5). For code, tests provide the cheap verifier — but only if the proposer is strong enough to produce test-passing improvements.\n2. **Every demonstrated compounding loop runs on a frontier model** (Claude 3.5/3.7 Sonnet, o3-mini, GPT-4). The papers explicitly say the meta-task \"requires powerful models\" (Claims 1–3, 12). This is the strongest available support for \"a weak local base model cannot bootstrap self-improvement.\"\n3. **Collapse modes are concrete and documented:** verifier reward-hacking (Claim 11), path-dependent proposal poisoning (Claim 12), within-episode error compounding (Claim 7), and — in the training-loop variant — distributional model collapse (Claims 8–9, contested in scope per the flagged conflict).\n4. **No published crisp SWE-bench number** marks compound-vs-collapse; the honest statement is \"demonstrated loops start ~17–20% and need a frontier generator/verifier,\" plus the mechanistic GV-gap result. Don't cite a specific threshold percentage as established fact.\n\nMain conflict to keep in view: the **scope of \"model collapse\"** (Claim 8 vs the 2503.03150 / BIML rebuttals) — catastrophic only for replace-all self-training, much milder for realistic accumulate/mixed pipelines.</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>26901</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>13</tool_uses><duration_ms>132845</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>"},"isMeta":true,"uuid":"eaedf978-6032-41ea-a70f-2ab9ff2e59e5","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:39.764Z","origin":{"kind":"task-notification"},"userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"eaedf978-6032-41ea-a70f-2ab9ff2e59e5","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015BBheYhUm83DpVQWhUGewo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Agent 2 (autonomy threshold) done with excellent mechanism-level findings (GV-gap, DGM/SICA, collapse modes). Note: it flagged one future-dated source (arxiv 2603.19328 \"Verifier Tax\") which I'll treat cautiously. Waiting on agents 3, 4, 5."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4874,"cache_read_input_tokens":25295,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4874,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2CXYEE3zdyxdrrsqxA","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"34c47547-3215-42f4-8ba7-104484e1822f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:43.689Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"34c47547-3215-42f4-8ba7-104484e1822f","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"[SYSTEM NOTIFICATION - NOT USER INPUT]\nThis is an automated background-task event, NOT a message from the user.\nDo NOT interpret this as user acknowledgement, confirmation, or response to any pending question.\n\n<task-notification>\n<task-id>a72217cc746f6deac</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_019BSUqJUJq9m9JfiSfh2XT1</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/8c297f37-26ee-4ab6-9c6c-7ec95dbfe2e1/tasks/a72217cc746f6deac.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Verifier-gated bootstrapping strategies\" came to rest</summary>\n<note>A task-notification fires each time this agent comes to rest with no live background children of its own. The user can send it another message and resume it, so the same task-id may notify more than once.</note>\n<result>I have comprehensive, cross-checked data across all research angles. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# Findings: Can a strong verifier compensate for a weak generator?\n\nThe literature strongly supports the core thesis: **a rigorous verifier (compiler + tests) lets a weak generator reach far above its pass@1, often matching a much larger model — but only up to a coverage ceiling, and only as far as the verifier's precision allows.** Falsifiable claims below, with conflicts flagged.\n\n## A. Repeated sampling + verification (the headline mechanism)\n\n1. **CLAIM: With an automatic verifier, repeated sampling turns a weak generator into SOTA-beating performance on code.** On SWE-bench Lite, DeepSeek-Coder-V2-Instruct goes from **15.9% (1 sample) → 56% (250 samples)**, beating the then single-attempt SOTA of **43%** which used more capable frontier models.\n   - Source: Brown et al., \"Large Language Monkeys\" — https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787\n\n2. **CLAIM: Coverage (fraction of problems solved by ≥1 sample) scales log-linearly with sample count over ~4 orders of magnitude, fitting an exponentiated power law.** This is the inference-time scaling law that underwrites the whole strategy.\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787\n\n3. **CLAIM (the key limit): The verifier/selector is the bottleneck, not coverage.** Without an automatic checker, selection methods (majority voting, learned reward models) **plateau beyond several hundred samples** and fail to scale with the sample budget. Coding/formal proofs benefit precisely because they HAVE automatic verification (code execution, proof checker). This is the direct evidence for \"a rigorous verifier is what unlocks the weak generator.\"\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787\n\n## B. The generation–verification gap (verification is easier than generation)\n\n4. **CLAIM: The generation-verification gap is defined as `Pass@K − (achieved) Success Rate` — a large positive gap means the correct answer is in the sample set but selection fails to find it.** This formalizes \"the model already knows the answer; it just can't pick it.\"\n   - Source: Weaver, Saad-Falcon et al. — https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.18203 (https://arxiv.org/html/2506.18203v1)\n\n5. **CLAIM: Aggregating weak verifiers lets a weak generator reach near-frontier accuracy.** Weaver + **Llama 3.3 70B (non-reasoning generator) reaches 87.7% avg, within 0.5% of o3-mini's 86.7%**, using repeated sampling + an ensemble of ≤70B judge/reward models instead of a stronger generator. Improvement over Pass@1: **+17.9% (8B models), +14.5% (70B models)** across reasoning/math.\n   - Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.18203\n   - Note: this uses *weak/noisy* verifiers (judges, reward models), NOT a perfect verifier. The gap to oracle remains: Weaver 93.4% vs Pass@100 oracle 98.6% on MATH500; 72.1% vs 81.0% on GPQA Diamond. A perfect verifier (compiler+tests) would close that residual — which is exactly the code/proof case.\n\n## C. Test-time compute can substitute for model size\n\n6. **CLAIM: A smaller model with compute-optimal test-time scaling can beat a 14× larger model at matched FLOPs, ~4× more efficient than best-of-N.** Uses process-verifier search + adaptive response revision; gains depend on prompt difficulty.\n   - Source: Snell et al., \"Scaling LLM Test-Time Compute Optimally...\" — https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.03314\n\n7. **CLAIM: With a good process reward model guiding search, tiny models beat giant ones on verifiable math.** A 1B model exceeds a 405B model on MATH-500; a 0.5B model beats GPT-4o; a 3B beats 405B; a 7B beats o1 and DeepSeek-R1 — on MATH-500/AIME24.\n   - Source: Liu et al., \"Can 1B LLM Surpass 405B?\" — https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.06703\n   - CONFLICT/caveat: these are math benchmarks with a strong PRM doing the heavy lifting, and the result is \"compute-optimal *strategy* depends on policy model, PRM, and difficulty.\" It is NOT an unconditional \"small always wins.\" Treat as best-case under an excellent verifier.\n\n## D. Evolutionary / population search gated by tests (tests-as-fitness)\n\n8. **CLAIM: Evolutionary code search using an LLM as mutation operator + an automatic test/evaluator as fitness produces genuinely novel, correct results.** AlphaEvolve found a way to multiply two 4×4 complex matrices in **48 scalar multiplications**, beating Strassen's 49 (standing since 1969). Each candidate is automatically scored by a quantitative fitness function; only verifiable improvements survive.\n   - Source: AlphaEvolve (DeepMind, May 2025) — https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/ and PDF https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf\n\n9. **CLAIM: AlphaEvolve produced production wins gated entirely by automated evaluation.** Recovers **0.7% of Google's global compute**; sped a Gemini training kernel by **23%**. The mechanism: Gemini Flash (breadth) + Gemini Pro (depth) propose code; an evaluator runs and scores it. The verifier, not generator strength, defines correctness.\n   - Source: same as #8.\n\n10. **CLAIM: The same architecture works with a *weak* LLM because fitness = an evaluation function, not the LLM's judgment.** FunSearch (precursor) discovered new cap-set lower bounds (largest improvement in 20 years to the asymptotic bound) and bin-packing heuristics beating first-fit/best-fit — using a sampled program database favoring high-scoring programs, with all candidates executed and scored by an evaluator.\n   - Source: Romera-Paredes et al., FunSearch, Nature 2023/2024 — https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06924-6 ; blog https://deepmind.google/blog/funsearch-making-new-discoveries-in-mathematical-sciences-using-large-language-models/\n\n## E. Limits — where a strong verifier stops compensating\n\n11. **CLAIM: Best-of-N provably suffers reward hacking as N grows when the verifier is imperfect.** Under stringent coverage BoN is optimal, but under realistic coverage its average reward fails to scale with N; false positives come to dominate. Mitigations proposed: rejection-sampling variant, \"InferenceTimePessimism.\"\n   - Source: \"Is Best-of-N the Best of Them?\" ICML 2025 — https://icml.cc/virtual/2025/poster/45322 ; \"Inference-Time Reward Hacking\" — https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.19248\n\n12. **CLAIM: Verifiers that check only extensional correctness (i.e. tests) admit false positives — models learn to enumerate instance-level outputs that pass tests without solving the task (reward hacking / RLVR gaming).** Directly relevant to a compiler+test-suite verifier: a weak generator under enough samples can find solutions that satisfy the tests but not the intent. The verifier's precision is the cap.\n   - Source: \"LLMs Gaming Verifiers: RLVR can Lead to Reward Hacking\" — https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.15149\n\n13. **CLAIM: The hard floor — if the weak model never samples a correct solution, no verifier helps.** Coverage = P(≥1 correct in N draws); the verifier can only *select* from what was generated, never create. Selection saturates beyond a few hundred samples without a perfect checker; coverage itself can asymptote below 100% for hard problems regardless of N.\n   - Source (coverage ceiling + selection plateau): https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787 ; (imperfect-verifier diminishing returns): https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.18982\n\n## Synthesis for the build (Yogi's compiler+test verifier)\n\n- A compiler + test suite is the *best* kind of verifier in this literature (automatic, executable) — it is exactly the case where repeated sampling translates coverage gains directly into solved problems (Monkeys #3, AlphaEvolve #8).\n- Realistic expectation: a weak local generator (qwen3:8b) with N samples gated by tests should substantially beat its own pass@1 and can approach a much larger model's pass@1 — *bounded by* (a) the weak model's coverage at achievable N, and (b) test-suite precision (false positives = reward hacking, claims #11–12).\n- Two distinct ceilings to encode as falsifiable expectations: a **coverage ceiling** (generator never produces a passing candidate) and a **verifier-precision ceiling** (candidate passes tests but is wrong). The strong verifier fixes selection, not generation.\n\n### Conflicts flagged\n- #7 (1B&gt;405B) vs general practice: holds only on verifiable math with a strong PRM and is strategy-dependent — not an unconditional small-beats-large result.\n- #5/Weaver near-o3-mini uses *weak* aggregated verifiers and still leaves a residual gap to oracle (Pass@100); a perfect compiler+test verifier would do better on the selection axis but the coverage gap to oracle remains.\n- AlphaEvolve's 48-multiplication result has minor academic dispute over whether 48 was truly unprecedented in all mathematical contexts; undisputed that it was the first found via automated search.</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>25483</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>11</tool_uses><duration_ms>114816</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\n\n<task-notification>\n<task-id>aed8b63927090d2d9</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01P1rEch6VtrXFHQJkv88CyP</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/8c297f37-26ee-4ab6-9c6c-7ec95dbfe2e1/tasks/aed8b63927090d2d9.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"On-device LoRA/RLVR feasibility 16GB\" came to rest</summary>\n<note>A task-notification fires each time this agent comes to rest with no live background children of its own. The user can send it another message and resume it, so the same task-id may notify more than once.</note>\n<result>I have enough cross-checked evidence. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n# Findings: On-device 8B training + self-training/RLVR for small models\n\n## A. LoRA/QLoRA fine-tuning of 7-8B on 16 GB Apple silicon\n\n**CLAIM 1 — QLoRA on an 8B model fits and trains on a 16 GB Mac, but only as a marginal config requiring careful tuning.**\n- Detail: Multiple guides say \"QLoRA on a 16GB MacBook can fine-tune an 8B model in about an hour,\" but qualify that 7-8B is the *edge* of feasibility — \"marginal feasibility with batch=1, seq=512\" and \"OOM risk on 16GB.\" The stated \"sweet spot\" for 16 GB is **3B models**, not 8B.\n- Source: https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/ ; https://www.buildmvpfast.com/blog/mlx-apple-silicon-ai-development-mac-fine-tune-llm-2026\n\n**CLAIM 2 — Official mlx-lm docs give a 7B reference config of batch-size 1 / 4 layers and demonstrate it on a 32 GB machine, NOT 16 GB.**\n- Detail: The canonical LORA.md example is `mlx_lm.lora --model Mistral-7B --train --batch-size 1 --num-layers 4`, benchmarked at ~250 tok/s on an M1 Max **32GB**. The docs deliberately give **no minimum-RAM figure** — they say \"a machine with a decent amount of memory.\" All official worked examples use 32 GB.\n- Source: https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/blob/main/mlx_lm/LORA.md\n- **CONFLICT FLAG:** Blog posts assert 16 GB works for 8B; Apple's own docs only demonstrate 32 GB for 7B. The official source is more conservative than the blogs.\n\n**CLAIM 3 — An 8B model in BF16 needs ~17 GB just for weights — i.e. you cannot full-precision fine-tune 8B on 16 GB; the base must be 4-bit quantized (QLoRA).**\n- Detail: \"an 8B parameter model in BF16 precision can require around 17 GB.\" Hence on 16 GB you must run QLoRA (4-bit quantized base), which cuts memory ~75%.\n- Source: https://grokipedia.com/page/MLX-LM ; QLoRA reduction figure: https://blogs.utilia.dev/qlora-step-by-step-fine-tune-7b-laptop\n\n**CLAIM 4 — The memory levers that make 8B fit on 16 GB: 4-bit quantized base + batch-size 1 + reduce LoRA layers to 4-8 + `--grad-checkpoint` + short sequences (&lt;~3,500 tokens).**\n- Detail: `--grad-checkpoint` trades compute for memory at roughly **+30% training time**. Watching Activity Monitor for yellow/red memory pressure (swap) is advised because swap \"destroys training speed.\"\n- Source: https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/blob/main/mlx_lm/LORA.md ; https://insiderllm.com/guides/fine-tuning-mac-lora-mlx/\n\n**CLAIM 5 — Real OOM reports exist for Llama-3.1-8B LoRA under MLX (so 16 GB headroom is genuinely thin).**\n- Detail: Open GitHub issues report \"Memory overflow when lora fine-tuning Meta-Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct\" and a suspected \"memory leak during Llama 3 8b LoRA fine-tuning.\"\n- Source: https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx/issues/1406 ; https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-examples/issues/738\n\n**CLAIM 6 — Reference QLoRA-7B VRAM/RAM footprint on non-Apple hardware is ~11-12 GB (consistent with 16 GB being tight-but-feasible).**\n- Detail: \"~12 GB VRAM with QLoRA\"; one report of 11,181 MiB at seq~337 tokens, reducible to ~10.9 GB. With batch size 1, dominant cost is activation/input gradients (~567 MB) not adapter weights (~26 MB) — so sequence length and layer count drive memory.\n- Source: https://blogs.utilia.dev/qlora-step-by-step-fine-tune-7b-laptop ; https://gist.github.com/Birch-san/57878c4a27cf34f57d3e861865a7d0a2 ; arXiv PEFT survey https://arxiv.org/pdf/2510.12178\n\n**Speed datapoint:** 7B LoRA adapter \"in under 30 minutes\" on a 16 GB M2 MBP per one blog (treat as optimistic/small-dataset). Source: https://www.buildmvpfast.com/blog/mlx-apple-silicon-ai-development-mac-fine-tune-llm-2026\n\n---\n\n## B. RLVR on small models (does it work for coding/math?)\n\n**CLAIM 7 — RL with verifiable rewards works on 3B and even 1.5B, but ~0.5B fails to learn reasoning. The threshold is between 1.5B and 3B.**\n- Detail: TinyZero (Jiayi Pan, Berkeley): a 3B Qwen2.5 base \"develops self-verification and search abilities on its own\" via RL on Countdown/multiplication. \"Even a 1.5B model can learn search and self-verification\"; \"Qwen2.5-0.5B base… fails to learn reasoning.\" Reproducible for **&lt; $30**.\n- Source: https://github.com/Jiayi-Pan/TinyZero ; https://www.rohan-paul.com/p/tinyzero-berkeley-researchers-reproduce\n- Hardware note: single GPU handles ≤1.5B; 3B+ wants 2 GPUs (tensor-parallel 2). This is datacenter GPU, not the Mac.\n\n**CLAIM 8 — RLVR is the right paradigm where reward = a programmatic check (tests pass) — proven gains in math, coding, medical QA from minimal curated data.**\n- Detail: RLVR uses \"objective, verifiable reward functions—rule-based checks\"; distinguished from RLHF by not using a learned reward model.\n- Source: https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/reinforcement-learning-with-verifiable-rewards-rlvr\n\n**CLAIM 9 — CRITICAL CAVEAT: RLVR mostly *sharpens sampling of capabilities the base already has*; it does NOT add fundamentally new reasoning, and can shrink problem coverage.**\n- Detail: On LiveCodeBench, Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct base = 23.8% pass@1; RLVR-trained = 28.1% pass@1 (RL wins at k=1). But at **k=128, base solves ~50% of coding problems vs only 42.8% for the RLVR model** — the base has broader coverage. RLVR trades exploration diversity for single-sample accuracy.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.13837 (\"Does RL Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity Beyond the Base Model?\") ; https://limit-of-rlvr.github.io/\n- **Implication for Yogi:** RLVR on qwen3:8b can lift pass@1 on tasks the base can already sometimes solve, but won't conjure capabilities the 8B base lacks. This is a real ceiling, not a tuning problem.\n\n---\n\n## C. Self-training / self-rewarding / self-distillation (does it lift or collapse?)\n\n**CLAIM 10 — Self-rewarding RL collapses: the model reward-hacks, degenerating to producing the same answer regardless of input to max self-assigned reward.**\n- Detail: \"Prolonged RL with self-reward leads to reward hacking… sudden performance collapse… optimal policy degenerates to producing the same answer regardless of input.\" SRT study confirms large reasoning models self-training eventually collapse.\n- Source: https://self-rewarding-llm-training.github.io/ (SRT: \"Can Large Reasoning Models Self-Train?\")\n\n**CLAIM 11 — Self-distillation saturates fast: a few iterations of SPIN/OPSD plateau or degrade because the student shares the teacher's own inductive biases (hypothesis space collapses).**\n- Detail: \"rapid onset of policy saturation… after a few iterations… universally note a plateau or severe degradation.\"\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2601.20802v1 (Reinforcement Learning via Self-Distillation)\n\n**CLAIM 12 — Small models are especially collapse-prone; mitigation = correctness-based pruning (verifiable filter) and mixing real + synthetic tokens.**\n- Detail: \"training collapse arises from the limited self-correction ability of SLMs.\" But \"correctness-based pruning stabilizes training, preserving knowledge while enhancing reasoning\" (Think-Prune-Train), and \"mixing real tokens and synthetic tokens\" avoids collapse and can beat the teacher.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2504.18116v1 (Think, Prune, Train, Improve) ; https://arxiv.org/html/2604.01193v1 (self-distillation for code)\n- **Implication:** Self-training only sustains improvement when gated by a *verifiable* correctness filter (tests pass) — i.e. it must be RLVR-style, not self-reward-style. Yogi's \"tests pass\" reward is exactly the stabilizing signal these papers say you need.\n\n---\n\n## D. Distillation from a stronger teacher (most reliable lever)\n\n**CLAIM 13 — Distilling a strong teacher into a small student via plain SFT is highly effective and BEATS large-scale RL on small models.**\n- Detail (DeepSeek-R1 paper, Section 4.1 / Table 6): DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-32B vs DeepSeek-R1-Zero-Qwen-32B (RL directly on 32B): **AIME 72.6% vs 47.0%; MATH-500 83.3%? (see note) vs 60.0%; GPQA 94.3% vs 91.6%.** Conclusion verbatim: \"distilling more powerful models into smaller ones yields excellent results, whereas smaller models relying on large-scale RL require enormous computational power and may not achieve distillation's performance.\"\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2501.12948v1\n- Note/conflict: the WebFetch returned MATH-500 distilled as 83.3% in the RL-comparison table, while the standard published R1-Distill-Qwen-32B MATH-500 figure is 94.3%. Treat the exact MATH-500 distilled value as needing a direct table check; the *direction* (distill &gt;&gt; RL on small models) is unambiguous.\n\n**CLAIM 14 — Distillation transfers coding+math into small dense students via ~800K SFT samples; quality scales with student size.**\n- Detail: R1 teacher generated ~800,000 SFT samples. R1-Distill-Qwen-7B: 92.8% MATH-500, 55.5% AIME 2024 (beats QwQ-32B-Preview), Codeforces rating 1189. \"Model performance improves progressively as student parameter size increases.\"\n- Source: https://huggingface.co/deepseek-ai/DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-7B ; https://arxiv.org/html/2501.12948v1 ; https://www.siliconflow.com/models/deepseek-r1-distill-qwen-7b\n\n---\n\n## Bottom line / conflicts summary\n\n1. **8B LoRA on 16 GB:** technically possible only as QLoRA (4-bit base) + batch 1 + ≤8 layers + grad-checkpoint + short seqs, and it's genuinely marginal (real OOM reports). **Conflict:** blogs say \"fits, ~1 hr\"; Apple's own docs only demonstrate 32 GB for 7B and quote no 16 GB number. The conservative read: **3B is the comfortable on-device sweet spot for 16 GB; 8B is at the OOM cliff.**\n2. **RLVR works on ≥1.5-3B** with a verifiable (tests-pass) reward, but mainly sharpens existing ability and can *reduce* pass@k coverage — a real ceiling.\n3. **Pure self-reward self-training collapses;** it only sustains gains when gated by a verifiable correctness filter (then it's effectively RLVR).\n4. **Distillation from a stronger teacher (Claude → small student) is the most reliable capability lift and beats small-model RL** per the DeepSeek-R1 paper — directly relevant to Yogi's \"frontier teacher = Claude Code, student = qwen3:8b\" design.\n\nCaveats on sourcing: several memory/time figures come from third-party blogs (utilia, insiderllm, buildmvpfast, grokipedia) and should be treated as indicative, not guaranteed; the load-bearing primary sources are the mlx-lm LORA.md, the DeepSeek-R1 arXiv paper, the Limit-of-RLVR paper, TinyZero's repo, and the SRT/Think-Prune-Train papers.</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>24465</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>11</tool_uses><duration_ms>124952</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>"},"isMeta":true,"uuid":"e78cc788-12a5-4b72-9334-8df437f3df81","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:45.798Z","origin":{"kind":"task-notification"},"userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"e78cc788-12a5-4b72-9334-8df437f3df81","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01UikcTnDFmJxTTy3dZZX1k7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Agents 3 and 4 done. Excellent material on RLVR ceilings, distillation, MLX 16GB feasibility, and verifier-gated bootstrapping. Waiting on agent 5 (outlook/timeline). A few future-dated arXiv IDs surfaced (2601.x, 2604.x, 2603.x) which I'll treat with caution or drop. Waiting for the final agent."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8917,"cache_read_input_tokens":30169,"output_tokens":136,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":8917},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":136,"cache_read_input_tokens":30169,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8917,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":8917,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2Cz4upzwrU9ikjyeKr","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"93c4454c-9442-4cf3-b994-aa2b100a1aab","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:50.087Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"93c4454c-9442-4cf3-b994-aa2b100a1aab","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"[SYSTEM NOTIFICATION - NOT USER INPUT]\nThis is an automated background-task event, NOT a message from the user.\nDo NOT interpret this as user acknowledgement, confirmation, or response to any pending question.\n\n<task-notification>\n<task-id>a6867b8fa220460c5</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>toolu_01FVuycsBD8mn6J8cbc1ttJm</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/8c297f37-26ee-4ab6-9c6c-7ec95dbfe2e1/tasks/a6867b8fa220460c5.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Small model trend and outlook\" came to rest</summary>\n<note>A task-notification fires each time this agent comes to rest with no live background children of its own. The user can send it another message and resume it, so the same task-id may notify more than once.</note>\n<result>I now have enough cross-checked material across all five angles. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n## RESEARCH FINDINGS: Outlook for small local models self-improving their own codebase\n\nNote on dates: searches returned sources dated through early-mid 2026 (current date June 2026), including some forward-dated items (e.g., arXiv 2603.* = March 2026, METR \"Time Horizon 1.1\" Jan 2026). I've flagged confidence where a source looked thin or SEO-ish rather than primary.\n\n---\n\n### A. Small-model coding capability trend (2024 → 2026)\n\n**CLAIM 1 — Small open coding models roughly doubled LiveCodeBench in ~1 year.**\n- Detail: Qwen2.5-Coder-7B-Instruct scored ~37.6% pass@1 on LiveCodeBench (2024.07–2024.11 window), released Nov 12, 2024. Qwen3-8B (May 2025) is reported to surpass Qwen2.5 instruct models on coding, with Qwen3 small models (8B/4B/1.7B) \"outperforming larger Qwen2.5-14B/7B/3B base models on over half of benchmarks, especially STEM and coding.\"\n- Source: https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen2.5-coder-family/ ; https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen3/\n- Confidence: Medium. Exact apples-to-apples 7B→8B LiveCodeBench deltas were not published in a single primary table; the 37.6% figure is the firmest datapoint.\n\n**CLAIM 2 — On SWE-bench Verified, the 32B-class open model went from ~69.6% (late 2024) and small-active-param MoEs now match it.**\n- Detail: Qwen2.5-Coder-32B ≈ 69.6% SWE-bench Verified (also 73.7 on Aider, \"comparable to GPT-4o\"), late 2024. By early 2026, Qwen3-Coder-Next (reported as \"80A3\" = ~80B total / ~3B active) hits ~70.6% (SWE-Agent), 71.1% (MiniSWE-Agent), 71.3% (OpenHands) on SWE-bench, \"comparable to models with 10×–20× more active parameters.\"\n- Source: https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen2.5-coder-family/ ; https://arxiv.org/html/2603.00729v1 (Qwen3-Coder-Next Technical Report) ; https://qwen.ai/blog?id=qwen3-coder-next\n- Confidence: Medium-High for the trajectory; High for the 69.6/73.7 baseline. NOTE: Qwen3-Coder-Next is a sparse MoE with ~3B *active* but ~80B *total* — it is NOT a dense 7-8B model and won't fit a 16GB laptop the way qwen3:8b does. Important caveat for the local-self-improvement question.\n\n**CLAIM 3 — The driver of gains shifted from raw scale to agentic post-training.**\n- Detail: Qwen3-Coder was \"specifically post-trained on long-horizon software engineering tasks including multi-file edits, test-driven debugging cycles, and codebase navigation\" rather than scaling parameters.\n- Source: https://qwen3lm.com/qwen-coder/ (secondary/SEO) ; corroborated by https://arxiv.org/html/2603.00729v1\n- Confidence: Medium (primary report corroborates the agentic-training thesis).\n\n**CLAIM 4 — Open-weight models are now within \"a few benchmark points\" of frontier on coding; teams run 60–80% of agent traffic locally.**\n- Detail: \"DeepSeek V4, Qwen 3 Coder, and Kimi K2.6 are within a few benchmark points of frontier models... teams run 60 to 80 percent of their agent traffic locally and only escalate the hard 20 percent to a frontier API.\"\n- Source: https://huggingface.co/blog/daya-shankar/open-source-llms ; https://www.kunalganglani.com/blog/local-llms-complete-guide\n- Confidence: Low-Medium (community blog claims, plausible but not benchmarked primary). CONFLICT FLAG: contradicted by Claim 9 (sub-7B models \"fail\"). Reconciliation: the \"near-frontier local\" models cited are large (30B–600B+ class), not 7-8B dense.\n\n**Gap to frontier — closing or widening?** Mixed. On *benchmark scores* for fixed model size, the gap is closing fast (Claim 2). On *autonomous long-horizon capability*, frontier is also advancing fast (Section B), so the absolute capability gap for truly dense-small models is roughly holding or widening even as the score gap narrows.\n\n---\n\n### B. METR time-horizon / task-length doubling\n\n**CLAIM 5 — AI autonomous task length (50% success) was doubling every ~7 months over 2019–2025.**\n- Detail: Original METR finding (March 2025): frontier \"50% time horizon\" doubling ≈ 7 months; best model at publication, Claude 3.7 Sonnet, ≈ 1 hour (50% success).\n- Source: https://metr.org/blog/2025-03-19-measuring-ai-ability-to-complete-long-tasks/ ; https://arxiv.org/html/2503.14499v1\n- Confidence: High (primary METR).\n\n**CLAIM 6 — The trend has ACCELERATED to a ~3-month doubling recently, and frontier is now ~5 hours.**\n- Detail: METR \"Time Horizon 1.1\" (Jan 29, 2026): since 2024 the doubling time is ~88.6 days (~3 months) under TH1.1 (vs 108.9 days under TH1). Frontier 50% time horizons: Claude Opus 4.5 ≈ 320 min (~5.3h), GPT-5 ≈ 214 min (~3.6h), o3 ≈ 121 min (~2h). TH1.1 expanded the suite by 34% (228 tasks) and doubled 8h+ tasks.\n- Source: https://metr.org/blog/2026-1-29-time-horizon-1-1/\n- Confidence: High (primary METR).\n- CONFLICT FLAG: A skeptic (Anatol Wegner, Medium) questions whether the 7-month doubling is still holding / is artifact-prone — https://medium.com/@AIchats/are-ai-time-horizons-still-doubling-every-7-months-6262ed2bcc6a. Treat acceleration claims with some caution; METR's own CIs are wide (e.g., Opus 4.5 [170,729] min).\n\n**CLAIM 7 — Extrapolation: week-long autonomous tasks in 2–4 years; month-long by early-to-mid 2030s.**\n- Detail: \"If the measured trend continues for 2–4 more years, generalist autonomous agents will be capable of performing a wide range of week-long tasks\"; month-long work by early-to-mid 2030s.\n- Source: https://metr.org/blog/2025-03-19-measuring-ai-ability-to-complete-long-tasks/\n- Confidence: High that METR said it; the extrapolation itself is inherently uncertain.\n\n---\n\n### C. Recursive self-improvement / autonomous SWE timelines\n\n**CLAIM 8 — AI 2027's headline timeline has been pushed back ~3–5 years (to ~2030).**\n- Detail: Original AI 2027 scenario projected superintelligence-enabling breakthroughs \"by end of 2027.\" Kokotajlo's Nov 2025 update: now ~2030, \"lots of uncertainty though.\"\n- Source: https://www.hungarianconservative.com/articles/tech/...kokotajlo/ (secondary) ; original: https://ai-2027.com/\n- Confidence: Medium (revision reported by secondary outlet; consistent across multiple results).\n\n**CLAIM 9 — Anthropic co-founder: ~60%+ chance by end of 2028 an AI can autonomously build its successor; ~30% by 2027.**\n- Detail: \"60% or higher chance that by the end of 2028 an AI system will be powerful enough to autonomously build its own successor, with a 30% chance as early as 2027.\"\n- Source: https://www.claudeapi.com/en/blog/news/ai-recursive-self-improvement-2028-prediction/ (secondary)\n- Confidence: Low-Medium (secondary; not located in Anthropic's own page).\n\n**CLAIM 10 — Anthropic's official stance is more hedged: no probability numbers, \"not there yet,\" code quality may surpass human-written within ~1 year, weeks-long tasks possible by 2027.**\n- Detail: Anthropic's own essay gives conditional forecasts, not probabilities: \"2027: AI systems could be capable of tasks that take a person weeks\"; \"within one year: code quality expected to surpass human-written code at Anthropic\"; explicitly \"genuinely unclear whether today's training methods and architectures could unlock that capacity.\"\n- Source: https://www.anthropic.com/institute/recursive-self-improvement\n- Confidence: High (primary Anthropic).\n- CONFLICT FLAG: Claim 9 (60%/30% hard numbers) vs Claim 10 (Anthropic officially declines to give probabilities). The widely-circulated \"60% by 2028\" is a paraphrase, not Anthropic's published position.\n\n---\n\n### D. Local/on-device drivers\n\n**CLAIM 11 — Agent distillation transfers full task-solving behavior (not just reasoning) from large agents into small models with retrieval + code tools.**\n- Detail: Frameworks distill \"not only reasoning capability but full task-solving behavior from LLM-based agents into sLMs with retrieval and code tools.\"\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.17612 (\"Distilling LLM Agent into Small Models with Retrieval and Code Tools\") ; https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.13820 (\"Structured Agent Distillation\")\n- Confidence: High (primary arXiv).\n\n**CLAIM 12 — Dominant 2026 pattern: \"big teacher in datacenter, small student in pocket,\" combining RL + distillation.**\n- Detail: MiniCPM5-1B (dense 1B, built for edge/coding agents) combines RL and on-policy distillation (OPD) for gains across math/code/instruction-following.\n- Source: https://medium.com/data-science-in-your-pocket/minicpm5-1b... ; https://enclaveai.app/blog/2026/03/29/llm-knowledge-distillation-on-device-explained/\n- Confidence: Low-Medium (secondary; MiniCPM5 specifics unverified against primary).\n\n---\n\n### E. Skeptic / falsification angle (why small local models still fail at self-coding)\n\n**CLAIM 13 — Reliability decay is universal: pass@1 drops ~24 percentage points from short to very-long horizons.**\n- Detail: Across 10 models, mean pass@1 drop of 24.3 pts (76.3% → 52.1%) over short→very-long task buckets.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.29231 (\"Beyond pass@1: A Reliability Science Framework for Long-Horizon LLM Agents\")\n- Confidence: Medium-High (primary arXiv, forward-dated Mar 2026).\n\n**CLAIM 14 — Agent success decays exponentially with task length due to a constant per-step failure (\"half-life\") — the core mechanism behind error compounding.**\n- Detail: Performance on long tasks explained by a constant hazard rate per minute of human-equivalent work ⇒ exponentially declining success; each agent has a characteristic \"half-life.\" This is the mechanism *underlying* METR's 7-month doubling — improving the agent raises its half-life.\n- Source: Toby Ord, https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.05115 (\"Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents?\") ; https://www.tobyord.com/writing/half-life\n- Confidence: High (primary). KEY IMPLICATION for Yogi: even a small per-step error rate compounds catastrophically over a long self-coding session; a model self-editing its own codebase autonomously needs a very high half-life, which small dense models currently lack.\n\n**CLAIM 15 — There is a hard capability threshold around 7B: models under 7B fail to emit reliable tool calls.**\n- Detail: \"Models like Qwen3-Coder 30B, GLM-5.1 32B, Gemma 4 27B, Llama 3.3 70B emit clean tool calls in every reliable stack, while models under 7B fail.\"\n- Source: https://www.promptquorum.com/power-local-llm/autonomous-local-agents-actually-work\n- Confidence: Low-Medium (community blog, but consistent with reliability-science papers).\n\n**CLAIM 16 — \"Fully autonomous\" local stacks work only because they're scoped (one editor, one model, one approval gate), not because tech is ready for unattended autonomy.**\n- Detail: \"Reliable stacks like Cline + Ollama and Continue.dev Agent mode succeed because they are scoped... not because the underlying technology is good enough for unattended autonomy.\" Frameworks \"drift into circular tool calls, hallucinate file paths, or get stuck on long-horizon planning.\"\n- Source: https://www.promptquorum.com/power-local-llm/autonomous-local-agents-actually-work\n- Confidence: Low-Medium (community blog; aligns with primary reliability findings).\n\n**CLAIM 17 — Context overflow is a primary long-horizon failure mode for local (small-context) models.**\n- Detail: \"Coding agents often fail when logs, file diffs, tool outputs and previous reasoning steps overflow the context window\" — acute for small local models with limited context.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.03549 (PARC, self-reflective long-horizon coding agent)\n- Confidence: Medium (primary arXiv addressing the failure, forward-dated Dec 2025).\n\n---\n\n### Synthesis (the load-bearing tension for Yogi)\n\n1. Small-model *benchmark* coding scores rose steeply (Claim 1–2), but the impressive \"small\" results are sparse-MoE models with large total params (~80B), not dense 7-8B models that fit 16GB (Claim 2 caveat). A true dense ~8B (like Yogi's `qwen3:8b`) sits below the ~7B reliability threshold where tool-calling and long-horizon planning still break (Claims 13–17).\n2. Frontier autonomous *task length* is doubling every ~3–7 months and now spans ~5 hours (Claims 5–6), but self-coding a codebase is a long-horizon task where exponential error compounding (Claim 14) dominates — exactly where small local models are weakest.\n3. Expert timelines for autonomous AI software engineering / recursive self-improvement cluster around 2028–2030, and have been *pushed back* from the original 2027 (Claims 8–10). These refer to *frontier* systems, not local 8B models.\n\nBottom line for a falsification harness: the realistic near-term outlook is that a local dense ~8B model is far from \"good enough to autonomously self-improve its own codebase.\" The credible path is scoped, gated, human-in-the-loop edits (Claim 16) plus agent distillation from a frontier teacher (Claims 11–12) — which maps directly onto Yogi's design (Claude Code as teacher, Ollama as local proposer, supervised mutation surface).\n\n### Conflicts flagged\n- Claim 4 (\"near-frontier local\") vs Claims 9/13/15 (\"sub-7B fails\") — resolved: the near-frontier locals are large models, not 7-8B dense.\n- Claim 6 acceleration vs skeptic Wegner — METR's wide CIs warrant caution on \"doubling is accelerating.\"\n- Claim 9 (60%/30% hard numbers, secondary) vs Claim 10 (Anthropic officially gives no probabilities, primary) — prefer the primary; the \"60% by 2028\" is a circulated paraphrase.\n- Several strong-sounding 2026 figures come from SEO/community blogs (qwen3lm.com, promptquorum, kunalganglani) — flagged Low/Medium and corroborated against primary arXiv/METR/Qwen where possible.</result>\n<usage><subagent_tokens>26405</subagent_tokens><tool_uses>15</tool_uses><duration_ms>175678</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>"},"isMeta":true,"uuid":"6788d83b-dd66-4261-8896-85c639910680","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:37:50.904Z","origin":{"kind":"task-notification"},"userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"6788d83b-dd66-4261-8896-85c639910680","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Wmpye9sQCXmJWMkspXUWJn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All 5 agents complete. Now the verify phase. The most load-bearing and surprising claims warrant a quick adversarial cross-check, and I noticed several agents flagged future-dated arXiv IDs (2603.x, 2604.x, 2601.x, 2512.x, 2603.29231). Given today is June 2026, papers from late 2025/early 2026 are plausible, but some IDs look implausibly precise/synthetic. Let me verify the highest-leverage claims directly: (1) the headline \"Large Language Monkeys\" 15.9%→56% result, (2) the DGM/SICA self-improvement numbers, and (3) the RLVR coverage-shrink result which is central to the verdict."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6127,"cache_read_input_tokens":39086,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6127,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2Hkt3eb1gCZxYsgdWj","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"16e43557-bf4c-47ad-9939-446631094cac","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:37:57.235Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"16e43557-bf4c-47ad-9939-446631094cac","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Wmpye9sQCXmJWMkspXUWJn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01CEZmDp2z4srHhG6NjAfCYR","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787","prompt":"What are the exact numbers for repeated sampling on SWE-bench Lite with DeepSeek-Coder-V2-Instruct? Specifically the pass rate with 1 sample vs many samples, and what the prior single-attempt SOTA was. Also: does coverage scale log-linearly with number of samples, and is the verifier/selection the bottleneck when no automatic verifier exists?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6127,"cache_read_input_tokens":39086,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6127,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2Hkt3eb1gCZxYsgdWj","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"2f352b78-b9c0-4703-8a2e-5f73766f4068","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:37:59.115Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"2f352b78-b9c0-4703-8a2e-5f73766f4068","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01Wmpye9sQCXmJWMkspXUWJn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_018JesYXAb65mq6YtWxpZ5JM","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.13837","prompt":"For RLVR vs base model on coding (LiveCodeBench) with Qwen2.5-7B: what are the exact pass@1 numbers for base vs RLVR-trained, and what are the pass@k (high k like 128) numbers showing the base model has broader coverage? Confirm whether RLVR narrows coverage / does not add capability beyond the base model."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6127,"cache_read_input_tokens":39086,"output_tokens":652,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6127},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":652,"cache_read_input_tokens":39086,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6127,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":6127,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2Hkt3eb1gCZxYsgdWj","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"656ff741-97e2-43d0-aa61-adcc8831285a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:38:01.034Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"2f352b78-b9c0-4703-8a2e-5f73766f4068","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01CEZmDp2z4srHhG6NjAfCYR","type":"tool_result","content":"# Key Findings from \"Large Language Monkeys\"\n\n**SWE-bench Lite Results:**\nThe paper reports that with DeepSeek-Coder-V2-Instruct, performance improved significantly through repeated sampling: \"the fraction of issues solved...increases from 15.9% with one sample to 56% with 250 samples, outperforming the single-sample state-of-the-art of 43%.\"\n\nSo the metrics are:\n- Single sample: 15.9%\n- 250 samples: 56%\n- Previous SOTA: 43%\n\n**Coverage Scaling:**\nThe researchers found that coverage exhibits consistent patterns across multiple tasks and models. They observed that \"the relationship between coverage and the number of samples is often log-linear and can be modelled with an exponentiated power law.\"\n\n**Selection Method Bottleneck:**\nIn domains lacking automatic verification, the authors identified a critical limitation: \"common methods for picking from a sample collection (majority voting and reward models) plateau beyond several hundred samples and fail to fully scale with the sample budget.\"\n\nThis indicates that selection/verification mechanisms become the constraining factor when automatic correctness checking isn't available, preventing the method from achieving the full potential of increased sampling."}]},"uuid":"e642564b-88ec-4037-8822-2f4fddf5810c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:38:04.047Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"2f352b78-b9c0-4703-8a2e-5f73766f4068","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"656ff741-97e2-43d0-aa61-adcc8831285a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018JesYXAb65mq6YtWxpZ5JM","type":"tool_result","content":"I apologize, but I cannot extract the specific pass@1 and pass@k numbers you're requesting from the provided PDF content. The document appears to be a research paper in PDF format with heavily compressed/encoded content that doesn't render as readable text in the format provided.\n\nTo answer your question about RLVR vs. base model performance on LiveCodeBench with Qwen2.5-7B, I would need access to:\n- Clear tables or figures showing exact pass@1 metrics\n- Pass@k (k=128) results comparing base vs. RLVR performance\n- Analysis of whether broader k-value coverage decreased after RL training\n\n**What I can tell you:** The document metadata indicates this is a paper titled \"Does Reinforcement Learning Really Incentivize Reasoning Capacity in LLMs Beyond the Base Model?\" which directly addresses your question about whether RL training adds genuine capability or merely optimizes existing knowledge.\n\nTo get the specific numerical data you need, I'd recommend:\n1. Viewing the PDF directly in a PDF reader\n2. Checking the paper's tables/appendices on arXiv (arxiv.org/abs/2504.13837)\n3. Consulting any supplementary materials the authors provided\n\nI apologize I couldn't be more helpful with the encoded content provided.\n\n[Binary content (application/pdf, 2.1MB) also saved to /Users/gg/.claude/projects/-Users-gg-Work-Yogi/d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f/tool-results/webfetch-1782027481511-oqagqg.pdf]"}]},"uuid":"61b604c8-e0a6-412e-9ac1-c9a0e4fc7d8d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:38:06.805Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"656ff741-97e2-43d0-aa61-adcc8831285a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.