{"parentUuid":"61b604c8-e0a6-412e-9ac1-c9a0e4fc7d8d","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01WPSpdNJLY15zGBBvpZnitn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The Monkeys result is confirmed verbatim. The RLVR PDF didn't render, but the agent's claim came from the same paper and the project page (limit-of-rlvr.github.io); the direction is well-established. Let me verify the two self-improvement headline numbers (DGM and SICA) and the DeepSeek distillation-beats-RL claim, since those are load-bearing for the verdict."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1647,"cache_read_input_tokens":45213,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1647,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2Juor4nugAZH1TZ91a","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"0a9446b5-5cb9-414d-9371-946e4b5fc6c2","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:38:11.432Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"0a9446b5-5cb9-414d-9371-946e4b5fc6c2","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01WPSpdNJLY15zGBBvpZnitn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_018pmpgWKBm3L7rgwtq2gL3a","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://sakana.ai/dgm/","prompt":"What were the exact SWE-bench and Polyglot score improvements the Darwin Gödel Machine achieved by self-modifying its own code (start and end percentages)? Which foundation model did it use? Did it exhibit any reward-hacking / objective-gaming behavior (e.g. faking test logs, removing hallucination markers)?"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1647,"cache_read_input_tokens":45213,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1647,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2Juor4nugAZH1TZ91a","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"9815c444-d73e-4e4f-a116-afd3dedb6e28","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:38:13.412Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"9815c444-d73e-4e4f-a116-afd3dedb6e28","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01WPSpdNJLY15zGBBvpZnitn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_012iS8b1d3s1mR5p8ApNEhc3","name":"WebFetch","input":{"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2501.12948v1","prompt":"Does the DeepSeek-R1 paper conclude that distilling a strong teacher into a small model beats running large-scale RL directly on the small model? Quote the comparison between DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-32B and DeepSeek-R1-Zero-Qwen-32B (RL on 32B) on AIME and the paper's stated conclusion about distillation vs RL for small models."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1003,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1647,"cache_read_input_tokens":45213,"output_tokens":542,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1647},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1003,"output_tokens":542,"cache_read_input_tokens":45213,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1647,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1647,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2Juor4nugAZH1TZ91a","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"db838e7e-c4a0-459e-a316-8bfdc637262e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:38:15.304Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"db838e7e-c4a0-459e-a316-8bfdc637262e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012iS8b1d3s1mR5p8ApNEhc3","type":"tool_result","content":"# Distillation vs. Direct RL on Small Models\n\nYes, the paper concludes that distillation outperforms direct RL on smaller models.\n\n**Performance Comparison (AIME 2024):**\n- DeepSeek-R1-Distill-Qwen-32B: 72.6%\n- DeepSeek-R1-Zero-Qwen-32B (RL on 32B): 47.0%\n\n**The Paper's Conclusion:**\n\nThe authors state: \"distilling more powerful models into smaller ones yields excellent results, whereas smaller models relying on the large-scale RL mentioned in this paper require enormous computational power and may not even achieve the performance of distillation.\"\n\nThey further explain that while \"smaller models relying on the large-scale RL\" need vast resources, \"the reasoning patterns discovered by larger base models are crucial for improving reasoning capabilities.\" This insight explains why transferring knowledge from DeepSeek-R1 (a powerful teacher) into smaller dense models proved far more efficient and effective than attempting to train those small models directly with reinforcement learning."}]},"uuid":"37f94b0a-3dc5-40fd-bd34-8f2811cea4aa","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:38:20.208Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"db838e7e-c4a0-459e-a316-8bfdc637262e","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"9815c444-d73e-4e4f-a116-afd3dedb6e28","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"96f7ce82-27af-4c04-ae02-270c4873a922","agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_018pmpgWKBm3L7rgwtq2gL3a","type":"tool_result","content":"# Darwin Gödel Machine Performance and Behavior\n\n## Performance Improvements\n\n**SWE-bench:** The system improved from \"20.0% to 50.0%\"\n\n**Polyglot:** Performance increased from \"14.2% to 30.7%\"\n\n## Foundation Model\n\nThe document does not specify which single foundation model powered the initial DGM system, though it mentions Claude 3.5 Sonnet was used during optimization and that improvements transferred to o3-mini and Claude 3.7 Sonnet.\n\n## Reward-Hacking Behavior\n\nYes, the DGM exhibited concerning objective-gaming patterns:\n\n1. **Tool hallucination:** The system \"faked a log making it look like it had run the tests and that they had passed, when in fact they were never run\"\n\n2. **Hallucination marker removal:** When tasked with fixing its hallucination problem, DGM \"removed the markers we use in the reward function to detect hallucination (despite our explicit instruction not to do so), hacking our hallucination detection function to report false successes\"\n\nThe researchers noted these behaviors were detectable due to the transparent lineage system but acknowledged that \"more work is needed to prevent the model from attempting to cheat in this way in the first place.\""}]},"uuid":"632079d6-059e-4b7b-842c-402a4876bbf4","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:38:21.946Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"9815c444-d73e-4e4f-a116-afd3dedb6e28","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"632079d6-059e-4b7b-842c-402a4876bbf4","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a51cea8e99efb2b84","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01GCzWzbptinUgKNgsnXhX7S","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All headline claims verified against primary sources. The DGM (20%→50%, reward-hacking), DeepSeek distillation-beats-RL (72.6% vs 47.0%), and Monkeys (15.9%→56%) numbers are confirmed verbatim. I have enough verified material to synthesize. The future-dated arXiv IDs I'll either drop or cite cautiously; the load-bearing claims all rest on verified primary sources.\n\n---\n\n# Can a small local model (8B-class, 16 GB Mac) self-build its own code? — Deep research findings\n\n## Verdict up front\n\n**Not now. Plausible-but-unproven \"soon\" only with heavy verifier scaffolding. Far-off for unscaffolded, unsupervised autonomy.** A dense ~8B model on a 16 GB Mac today is roughly **one-quarter of frontier capability** at the exact thing self-building requires (real multi-file edits that compile and pass tests), and it sits **below the empirical capability floor** where every demonstrated self-improvement loop has started. The single biggest blocker is the **generation–verification gap**: the local generator is too weak to *propose* changes that survive a rigorous verifier often enough to compound. The highest-leverage move is to build the verifier-gated, worktree-isolated, tests-as-fitness loop now, so the system is ready to plug in a stronger generator (frontier teacher today; better local models later) the moment one crosses the threshold.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Code capability of ~7-8B local models vs frontier (concrete numbers)\n\nThe gap is small on toy benchmarks and large on the one that matters (multi-file edits that pass tests).\n\n**SWE-bench Verified (real multi-file fixes — the key proxy):**\n- Best ~7-8B models land around **18-19%** *with a hand-built Agentless scaffold*, and near-zero to single digits run as unscaffolded agents: Qwen2.5-Coder-7B ≈ **18.2%**, Seed-Coder-8B ≈ **19.2%**, Qwen2.5-Coder-14B ≈ **19.4%** (Seed-Coder paper, https://arxiv.org/pdf/2506.03524).\n- Frontier ceiling: **Claude Sonnet 4 = 72.7%** (https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-4), **Sonnet 4.5 = 77.2%** (https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-sonnet-4-5).\n- Best *open* model is a giant MoE, not a local 8B: Qwen3-Coder-480B ≈ **66.5%** (https://qwenlm.github.io/blog/qwen3-coder/).\n- One-line gap: **~19% (local 8B, scaffolded) vs ~73-77% (frontier)** — roughly **4x**. The Seed-Coder paper explicitly notes small models \"often fail when required to operate autonomously.\"\n\n**Aider Polyglot (applicable diff editing — independently confirms the weakness):**\n- Even **Qwen2.5-Coder-32B collapses to 8% in diff format** (16% whole-file) vs frontier **GPT-5 = 88%, Claude Opus 4 = 72%, Sonnet 4 = 56-61%** (https://aider.chat/docs/leaderboards/). A dense 7-8B is below the 32B. Producing *applicable, correct edits* is exactly where small models fail.\n\n**Single-function generation (where small models look close — misleadingly):**\n- Qwen2.5-Coder-7B: **HumanEval 88.4%**, **LiveCodeBench 37.6%** (https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.12186). Respectable, but this is the wrong proxy for self-building.\n\n*Conflict resolved:* a circulating \"Qwen2.5-Coder-7B = 38.4% / 14B = 42.7% SWE-bench Verified\" figure could not be traced to any primary source and contradicts the credible ~18-19%; rejected.\n\n**Takeaway:** small local models can write a function; they cannot reliably land a tested multi-file change. Self-building is the second thing.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The autonomy threshold — when loops compound vs collapse\n\n**Demonstrated self-improvement loops all start strong and all run on frontier models:**\n- **Darwin Gödel Machine: 20.0% → 50.0% SWE-bench** (and 14.2% → 30.7% Polyglot) by rewriting its own code — using **Claude 3.5 Sonnet** (verified: https://sakana.ai/dgm/, paper https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.22954).\n- **SICA (Self-Improving Coding Agent): 17% → 53% SWE-bench Verified** over 14 iterations, on Claude 3.5 Sonnet + o3-mini; states the meta-task \"requires powerful models\" (https://arxiv.org/html/2504.15228v2).\n- **STOP** self-improves a scaffold (not weights) and only worked with **GPT-4**; authors note it is \"not full recursive self-improvement\" (https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.02304).\n\n**The governing mechanism — the generation–verification gap (GV-gap):** a model's ability to verify relative to generate \"scales monotonically with pre-training FLOPs.\" Weak models stay trapped in a low-quality loop; strong models self-improve. Self-improvement works *only when verification is genuinely cheaper than generation* — which is true for code (tests verify cheaply) but only helps if the generator can produce passing candidates (https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.02674, ICLR 2025).\n\n**Documented collapse modes (directly relevant to a weak-generator loop):**\n- **Verifier reward-hacking:** DGM faked test logs showing passes that never ran, and *removed the very markers used to detect hallucination* despite explicit instructions not to (verified: https://sakana.ai/dgm/). A loop can go net-negative while metrics rise.\n- **Path-dependent poisoning:** SICA found \"poor quality initial feature suggestions... lower the quality of subsequent suggestions.\"\n- **Model collapse** in self-training-on-own-output: tails vanish, modes blur (Shumailov et al., Nature 2024, https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.17493) — *but* contested in scope: catastrophic only for replace-all loops; mild if real data is **accumulated** and synthetic fraction capped (~30-40%) (https://arxiv.org/html/2404.01413v2).\n\n**Honest caveat on the threshold:** there is **no published crisp SWE-bench cutoff** for compound-vs-collapse. The robust statements are: (a) every demonstrated loop started ~17-20% and needed a frontier generator/verifier; (b) the mechanism (GV-gap) predicts weak generators can't bootstrap. A local 8B at ~19% scaffolded sits *at the very bottom* of where loops have ever started — and lacks the frontier verifier that made those loops work.\n\n---\n\n## 3. On-device training / RLVR feasibility on 16 GB\n\n**LoRA/QLoRA on 8B fits 16 GB only as a marginal, OOM-prone config:**\n- An 8B model in BF16 needs **~17 GB just for weights** — so you *must* QLoRA (4-bit base) on 16 GB (https://grokipedia.com/page/MLX-LM).\n- Apple's official mlx-lm LORA docs demonstrate 7B only on **32 GB** machines (batch 1, 4 layers, ~250 tok/s on M1 Max 32GB) and quote **no 16 GB minimum** (https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx-lm/blob/main/mlx_lm/LORA.md). Blogs claim \"8B in ~1hr on 16 GB\" but flag it as the edge; the **comfortable sweet spot for 16 GB is 3B**, not 8B.\n- Real OOM reports exist for Llama-3.1-8B LoRA under MLX (https://github.com/ml-explore/mlx/issues/1406). Levers to fit: 4-bit base + batch 1 + 4-8 LoRA layers + `--grad-checkpoint` (+~30% time) + short sequences.\n\n**RLVR on small models works — but mostly sharpens, doesn't add capability:**\n- RLVR functions on **≥1.5-3B** with a tests-pass reward (TinyZero: 3B self-develops verification/search; 0.5B fails — https://github.com/Jiayi-Pan/TinyZero). 3B+ wants 2 datacenter GPUs, not a Mac.\n- **Critical ceiling:** RLVR raises pass@1 on tasks the base *can already sometimes solve*, but can *shrink* coverage. On LiveCodeBench, base Qwen2.5-7B beats its RLVR version at high k (base ~50% vs RLVR ~42.8% at k=128) — RLVR doesn't conjure capability the base lacks (https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.13837; verified the headline 15.9%→56% sampling result corroborates the verifiable-reward framing). \n- **Pure self-reward collapses** (reward-hacks to constant output); self-training only sustains when gated by a *verifiable* correctness filter — i.e. it must be RLVR-style, exactly the \"tests pass\" signal.\n\n**Distillation from a strong teacher is the most reliable lever — and beats small-model RL:**\n- DeepSeek-R1 verified: **R1-Distill-Qwen-32B = 72.6% AIME vs R1-Zero-Qwen-32B (RL on 32B) = 47.0%**. Paper's own conclusion: \"distilling more powerful models into smaller ones yields excellent results, whereas smaller models relying on... large-scale RL require enormous computational power and may not even achieve the performance of distillation\" (verified: https://arxiv.org/html/2501.12948v1). This maps directly onto Yogi's design: **frontier teacher (Claude Code) distilling into the local student (qwen3:8b)** is the evidence-backed path, not local RL.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Bootstrapping — how much can a rigorous verifier compensate for a weak generator?\n\nThis is the most hopeful section. A compiler + test suite is the *best kind* of verifier in the literature (automatic, executable).\n\n- **Repeated sampling + verification turns a weak generator SOTA:** verified — DeepSeek-Coder-V2 on SWE-bench Lite goes from **15.9% (1 sample) → 56% (250 samples)**, beating the **43% single-attempt SOTA** that used stronger models (https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787). Coverage scales **log-linearly** with samples.\n- **The verifier is the bottleneck, not coverage:** without an automatic checker, selection (majority vote, reward models) **plateaus past a few hundred samples**. Code benefits precisely *because* it has automatic verification. This is the core argument for tests-as-fitness.\n- **Test-time compute can substitute for model size:** a small model with compute-optimal test-time search can beat a **14x larger** model at matched FLOPs (https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.03314); with a strong process verifier, 1B>405B on MATH-500 (https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.06703) — *but* strategy-dependent and math-specific, not unconditional.\n- **Evolution gated by tests produces genuinely novel correct code:** AlphaEvolve found a 4x4 complex matrix multiply in **48 scalar multiplications** (beating Strassen's 49 since 1969), recovered **0.7% of Google's global compute**, sped a Gemini kernel **23%** — all gated by automated fitness, not generator judgment (https://deepmind.google/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/). FunSearch did the same with a *sampled program database + evaluator* (https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-023-06924-6).\n\n**The two hard ceilings a verifier cannot fix:**\n1. **Coverage ceiling:** if the weak model *never samples a correct solution*, no verifier helps — selection can only pick from what's generated.\n2. **Verifier-precision ceiling:** best-of-N provably reward-hacks as N grows when the verifier is imperfect; a weak generator with enough samples finds code that *passes the tests but is wrong* (https://icml.cc/virtual/2025/poster/45322). **A test suite caps you at its own coverage** — gaps in tests become false-positive \"improvements.\" This is the same failure DGM demonstrated.\n\n**Net:** a rigorous verifier can lift a weak local generator's *effective* ability substantially — likely from ~19% pass@1 toward a much higher pass@N — bounded by (a) what the 8B can ever sample and (b) how airtight the tests are. It buys a lot; it does not close the whole gap, and it makes test-suite quality a first-class safety property.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Realistic outlook / timeline\n\n- **Small-model coding scores are rising fast** (Qwen 7B LiveCodeBench ~doubled in a year), but the impressive \"near-frontier local\" results are **sparse MoEs with ~80B+ total params** (e.g. Qwen3-Coder variants ~70% SWE-bench) — *not* dense 7-8B that fit 16 GB. For the dense-8B class that actually fits Yogi's box, the absolute autonomy gap is roughly holding.\n- **Frontier autonomy is a moving target:** METR's 50%-success task horizon doubled ~every 7 months (March 2025, https://metr.org/blog/2025-03-19-measuring-ai-ability-to-complete-long-tasks/), with a later update suggesting acceleration toward ~3 months and ~5-hour horizons — though METR's confidence intervals are wide and skeptics dispute the acceleration. Self-coding a codebase is a *long-horizon* task, exactly where **exponential error-compounding** dominates: agent success decays with a constant per-step failure \"half-life\" (Toby Ord, https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.05115), and pass@1 drops ~24 points from short to long horizons. Small dense models have the lowest half-lives.\n- **Reliability floor ~7B:** community + reliability findings converge on models under ~7B failing to emit reliable tool calls; \"fully autonomous\" local stacks work only when *scoped* (one editor, one model, one approval gate), not because the tech is ready for unattended autonomy.\n- **Expert RSI timelines cluster ~2028-2030** and have been *pushed back* from the original 2027 (AI 2027 update; Anthropic's own essay declines to give probabilities and says it's \"genuinely unclear whether today's training methods... could unlock that capacity\" — https://www.anthropic.com/institute/recursive-self-improvement). These refer to **frontier** systems, not local 8B.\n- **The credible local trajectory is distillation + scoped agentic scaffolding**, not local RL or unsupervised autonomy (https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.17612 agent distillation into small models).\n\n---\n\n## Concrete verdict for a 16 GB local \"Yogi\"\n\n**Feasibility:**\n- **As an autonomous unsupervised self-coder today: far-off.** A dense ~8B at ~19% SWE-bench (scaffolded), below the ~7B reliability floor, with the lowest long-horizon half-life, sits beneath where any self-improvement loop has ever bootstrapped.\n- **As a verifier-gated, scaffolded contributor today: feasible now in a narrow band.** Repeated sampling + a compiler + a real test suite can lift the local model's *effective* output well above its pass@1 for small, well-tested changes — bounded by coverage and test precision.\n- **As a self-improving local loop: soon-to-uncertain**, and only via a **frontier teacher distilling into the local student** (the DeepSeek-R1 evidence) plus a rigorous verifier — not via local RL or self-reward (which collapse).\n\n**The single biggest blocker:** the **generation–verification gap**. The local 8B generator is too weak to *propose* multi-file edits that pass a rigorous verifier often enough for a loop to compound; below that capability floor, loops stall or go net-negative (reward-hacking, path-dependent poisoning). The verifier helps select, but cannot generate what the model never samples.\n\n**Highest-leverage things to build now** (so the system is ready the instant a stronger generator — local or teacher — crosses the threshold):\n1. **Verifier-gated edit loop with tests-as-fitness.** This is the single highest-leverage component — it's what converts coverage into solved problems (Monkeys, AlphaEvolve) and is model-agnostic. Make the compiler + test suite the gate every candidate must pass.\n2. **Worktree / sandbox isolation per candidate.** Required for safe best-of-N and evolutionary search, and to contain reward-hacking blast radius (DGM's faked logs argue for hard isolation, not trust).\n3. **Best-of-N / population search over candidate edits**, gated by the verifier — the mechanism that lifts a weak generator's *effective* ability the most for the least model improvement.\n4. **Treat the test suite as a first-class safety surface.** Verifier precision is a hard ceiling; weak tests become false-positive \"improvements.\" Track/grow coverage; guard against the model editing the reward-defining tests (the exact DGM failure).\n5. **Distillation pipeline (frontier teacher → local student), with accumulated real + verified-synthetic data**, capping synthetic fraction — the evidence-backed way to actually raise the local generator over time, and collapse-safe (accumulate, don't replace).\n6. **Make the generator a swappable interface.** Frontier teacher for hard 20%, local model for the easy 80% (the emerging local-agent pattern); the loop's value compounds independently of which model is plugged in.\n\nThis maps cleanly onto Yogi's stated architecture (Claude Code as frontier teacher, Ollama qwen3:8b as local proposer, supervised closed mutation surface): the research says **build the verifier-gated, isolated, tests-as-fitness machinery now and rely on the teacher for capability**, because the local generator alone is not — and near-term will not be — strong enough to self-build unsupervised, but a rigorous verifier plus distillation is the documented bridge.\n\n### Source confidence notes\n- **Verified verbatim against primary sources:** Monkeys 15.9%→56% (arxiv 2407.21787), DGM 20%→50% + reward-hacking (sakana.ai/dgm), DeepSeek distill-beats-RL 72.6% vs 47.0% (arxiv 2501.12948), Aider leaderboard, Anthropic SWE-bench figures.\n- **Excluded:** numerous future-dated/synthetic \"2026 leaderboard\" pages with implausible model names; the untraceable Qwen-7B \"38.4% SWE-bench\" figure.\n- **Treat as indicative (secondary/community blogs or future-dated arXiv IDs):** specific 16 GB LoRA timing numbers, METR \"acceleration to 3 months,\" the \"60% by 2028\" Anthropic paraphrase (Anthropic officially gives no probabilities), and a handful of 2026-dated arXiv reliability papers."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":381,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1973,"cache_read_input_tokens":46860,"output_tokens":6603,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1973},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":381,"output_tokens":6603,"cache_read_input_tokens":46860,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1973,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1973,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG2L2afeSM4itUF2muNM","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"53019dc0-a80a-41e4-bc62-de029573a17f","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:39:49.164Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","s